article.headline: Wildcats' 35-game home winning streak ends
article.linkText: Without Wecker, K-State falls to Liberty
article.story:
MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Liberty took advantage of Kansas State (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 19 AP) without Kendra Wecker, snapping the Wildcats' 35-game regular-season home winning streak 77-56 on Saturday.

It marked Kansas State's worst home loss since Feb. 18, 1998. Wecker, a preseason All-American and the Wildcats' leading scorer, injured her left ankle against New Hampshire on Friday night.

Kristal Tharp led Liberty (3-2) with 26 points in the championship game of the Wildcat Classic. Katie Feenstra, the tournament MVP, had 22 points and eight rebounds. Rima Margeviciute added 16 for the Flames, who jumped out to a 10-2 lead in the first 4:51.

Megan Mahoney lead Kansas State (4-2) with 18 points. Laurie Koehn added 17 for the Wildcats, who were only 5-of-24 on 3-pointers and 3-of-10 from the free-throw line.

Wecker averaged a team-high 20.6 points and 7.6 rebounds before the injury.

Leading 36-35 with 18:04 left, Liberty used a 21-2 run for a 57-37 lead. Tharp hit back-to-back 3s to start the spurt.

Liberty led by as many as 24 in the second half, despite turning the ball over 23 times. The flames shot 54 percent and outrebounded Kansas State 42-26.

Margeviciute and Tharp joined Mahoney and Koehn on the all-tournament team.

New Hampshire beat Tennessee State 66-42 in the tournament's consolation game.
